Two threads, accessing a non-atomic, non-guarded variable are [U.B.](https://stackoverflow.com/a/4105123/1505939) This concerns `finished`. You could make `finished` of type `std::atomic&lt;bool&gt;` to fix this.

My fix:
```
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;future&gt;
#include &lt;atomic&gt;

static std::atomic&lt;bool&gt; finished = false;

int func()
{
    size_t i = 0;
    while (!finished)
        ++i;
    return i;
}

int main()
{
    auto result=std::async(std::launch::async, func);
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(1));
    finished=true;
    std::cout&lt;&lt;&quot;result =&quot;&lt;&lt;result.get();
    std::cout&lt;&lt;&quot;\nmain thread id=&quot;&lt;&lt;std::this_thread::get_id()&lt;&lt;std::endl;
}
```
Output:
```none
result =1023045342
main thread id=140147660588864
```
&lt;kbd&gt;[**Live Demo on coliru**](http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/a/c638ef4ff3965010)&lt;/kbd&gt;

---

Somebody may think &#39;It&#39;s a `bool` &amp;ndash; probably one bit. How can this be non-atomic?&#39; (I did when I started with multi-threading myself.)

However, making a `bool` unguarded, non-atomic can cause additional issues:

- The compiler might decide to optimize variable into a register.
- The variable might be cached for a CPU core.

To prevent this to happen, the compiler must be told explicitly not to do.

For the sake of completeness in the learning curve; you should avoid using global variables. You did a good job though by making it static, so it will be local to the translation unit.

Here is an example:

```
class ST {
public:
    int func()
    {
        size_t i = 0;
        while (!finished)
            ++i;
        return i;
    }
    void setFinished(bool val)
    {
        finished = val;
    }
private:
    std::atomic&lt;bool&gt; finished = false;
};

int main()
{
    ST st;
    auto result=std::async(std::launch::async, &amp;ST::func, std::ref(st));
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(1));
    st.setFinished(true);
    std::cout&lt;&lt;&quot;result =&quot;&lt;&lt;result.get();
    std::cout&lt;&lt;&quot;\nmain thread id=&quot;&lt;&lt;std::this_thread::get_id()&lt;&lt;std::endl;
}
```
